===Etymology===
[[French]]: ''pastiche'', from [[Italian]]: ''pasticcio''

===Noun===
'''pastiche'''
# A [[work]] of [[drama]], [[literature]], or [[music]] that [[imitate]]s the work of a [[previous]] [[artist]], often [[satirically]].
# A [[musical]] [[medley]].
# An [[incongruous]] [[mixture]]; a [[hodgepodge]].
# A postmodern playwriting technique that fuses a variety of styles, genres, and story lines to create a new form. 


An example of a literary pastiche is Stoppard's "Rosencrantz and Guildenstern Are Dead," which draws upon Shakespeare's Hamlet and Beckett's Waiting for Godot (absurdist theater), resulting in a new form that emphasizes the existentialist themes that both earlier works share.  A cinematic example of a pastiche is the blockbuster "Matrix," which draws upon film conventions from numerous genres, including Film noir, Kung-Fu films, and Science Fiction.  

